  <para id="para-00019">Another thing worth mentioning here and something that appears to be an unusual offering is part of the American Express Gold and higher level cards. You can actually open a savings account, buy a CD, or apply for a personal or business loan from American Express. The company boasts a higher interest rate than what is paid on traditional savings accounts and CDs.</para>
  </section>
  </section>
  <section id="sect-00003">
  <title>Average Daily Balance</title>
  <para id="para-00020">Most credit card companies compute interest using the Average Daily Balance method.</para>
  <example id="exam-00001">
  <title>Computing Average Daily Balance, Finance Charge, and Balance</title>
  <exercise id="exer-00001">
  <problem id="prob-00001">
  <para id="para-00021">Suppose your credit card company charges an annual interest rate of 19.2%, or 1.6% a month on the average daily balance. Your billing period for May goes from May 1 to May 30, and on May 1 your previous balance was $450.</para>
  <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" id="list-00002">
  <item>Compute the average daily balance for the next billing cycle (May 30).</item>
  <item>Compute the finance charge that will appear on the next bill.</item>
  <item>Compute the balance on May 30.</item>
  </list>
  <para id="para-00022">Here is a list of the activity on your card for May:</para>
  <table class="unnumbered" summary="." id="table-00001">
  <tgroup cols="3">
  <colspec colnum="1" colname="c1" colwidth="1*"/>
  <colspec colnum="2" colname="c2" colwidth="1*"/>
  <colspec colnum="3" colname="c3" colwidth="1*"/>
  <thead>
  <row>
  <entry>Date</entry>
  <entry>Activity</entry>
  <entry>Amount</entry>
  </row>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
  <row>
  <entry>May 1</entry>
  <entry>Billing Date Balance</entry>
  <entry>$450.21</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 10</entry>
  <entry>Payment</entry>
  <entry>$120.00</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 15</entry>
  <entry>Groceries</entry>
  <entry> $83.43</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 26</entry>
  <entry>Auto Parts</entry>
  <entry> $45.12</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 30</entry>
  <entry>Shoes</entry>
  <entry> $98.23</entry>
  </row>
  </tbody>
  </tgroup>
  </table>
  </problem>
  <solution id="sol-00001">
  <list list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" id="list-00003">
  <item>To compute your average daily balance, make a table showing all the transactions for the billing cycle including a running balance.
  <table class="unnumbered" summary="." id="table-00002">
  <tgroup cols="2">
  <colspec colnum="1" colname="c1" colwidth="1*"/>
  <colspec colnum="2" colname="c2" colwidth="1*"/>
  <thead>
  <row>
  <entry>Date</entry>
  <entry>Running Balance</entry>
  </row>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
  <row>
  <entry>May 1</entry>
  <entry>$450.21</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 10</entry>
  <entry>$450.21 – $120.00 = $330.21</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 15</entry>
  <entry>$330.21 + $83.43 = $413.64</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 26</entry>
  <entry>$413.64 + $45.12 = $458.76</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 30</entry>
  <entry>$458.76 + $98.23 = $556.99</entry>
  </row>
  </tbody>
  </tgroup>
  </table>
  <para id="para-00023">The next step is to make another table that lists the running balances and the number of days until the balance changed. Multiply the number of days by each balance.</para>
  <table class="unnumbered" summary="." id="table-00003">
  <tgroup cols="4">
  <colspec colnum="1" colname="c1" colwidth="1*"/>
  <colspec colnum="2" colname="c2" colwidth="1*"/>
  <colspec colnum="3" colname="c3" colwidth="1*"/>
  <colspec colnum="4" colname="c4" colwidth="1*"/>
  <thead>
  <row>
  <entry>Date</entry>
  <entry>Running Balance</entry>
  <entry>Number of days until Balance Changed</entry>
  <entry><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mtable columnalign="left"><mtr columnalign="left"><mtd columnalign="left"><mrow><mtext>Running</mtext></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr columnalign="left"><mtd columnalign="left"><mrow><mtext>Balance</mtext></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mtext>•</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mtable columnalign="left"><mtr columnalign="left"><mtd columnalign="left"><mrow><mtext>Number</mtext></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr columnalign="left"><mtd columnalign="left"><mrow><mtext>of Days</mtext></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></math></entry>
  </row>
  </thead>
  <tbody xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">
  <row>
  <entry>May 1</entry>
  <entry>$450.21</entry>
  <entry>9</entry>
  <entry>$4,051.89</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 10</entry>
  <entry>$330.21</entry>
  <entry>5</entry>
  <entry>$1,651.05</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 15</entry>
  <entry>$413.64</entry>
  <entry>11</entry>
  <entry>$4,550.04</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 26</entry>
  <entry>$458.76</entry>
  <entry>4</entry>
  <entry>$1,835.04</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry>May 30</entry>
  <entry>$556.99</entry>
  <entry>2</entry>
  <entry>$1,113.98</entry>
  </row>
  <row>
  <entry/>
  <entry>Totals</entry>
  <entry>31</entry>
  <entry>$13,202.00</entry>
  </row>
  </tbody>
  </tgroup>
  </table>
  <para id="para-00024">The average daily balance <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mtext>Sum of daily balances</mtext></mrow><mrow><mtext>Days in billing cycle</mtext></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>$</mi><mn>13202</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>31</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>$</mi><mn>425.87</mn></mrow></math></para></item>
  <item xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">The interest charge for May comes to <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>$</mi><mn>425.87</mn><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>0.016</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>$</mi><mn>6.81.</mn></mrow></math></item>
  <item xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">The balance on May 31 will be <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>$</mi><mn>556.99</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>$</mi><mn>6.81</mn><mo>=</mo><mi>$</mi><mn>563.80.</mn></mrow></math></item>
  </list>
  </solution>
  </exercise>
